Hi friends,

I've been taking this week off Instagram. I felt a bit stagnant last week and noticed my screen time was up 40% and I was averaging 2 hours a day on Instagram, which is extremely high for me. i.e. I was using IG to numb out (I know y'all can relate!)

So I did some more math.

There are 168 hours total in a week. Minus 56 for sleep. Minus 40 for work. Minus 20 for all the life admin nobody puts on their vision board like commuting, errands, working out, and eating.

That leaves us with 52 hours left. Every single week!

That's a lot of time. Like a full time job kinda time. And most of us have no real answer for where it goes.

So my 2 hours a day on Instagram = 14 hours a week. Add the 10-12 hours of shows and movies I watched and suddenly I'd handed roughly 26 of my 52 free hours straight to consumption. Half gone just like that.

I love a new Netflix show, but Is it really beneficial for me to allocate 14 of those precious hours to the mighty overlord of Meta?! I'm not here to shame anyone. Or myself. But that number made me pause.

Because the shift I've noticed is this: I genuinely feel better when I'm CREATING than when I'm CONSUMING. New connections with people. New projects. New hobbies and skills (new neural pathways being built in your brain). Deep conversations that stay with you for days.

That stuff fills me up. The scroll doesn't.

We are made to create. And it's way too easy to just default into consumption mode without ever actually choosing it.

Those 52 hours are yours. Completely yours.

I just want you to be aware — and make the choice for yourself.

Because there's a big difference between deciding to watch a great show or giving yourself time to catch up on social media and letting the algorithm tuck you in every night.

Here's to your 52,

Joshua "Create Don't Consume" Church

