Hi friends,

Steam was rolling off my mug when I noticed the tension at the table next to me.

A couple was sitting there, and a woman and her older mom had just asked if they could share the table since there was nowhere else to sit. The couple said yes, of course, but you could feel it — that little cloud of awkward that shows up whenever strangers are suddenly sharing the same square footage.

And then I watched it happen.

Small talk started inching toward the deep end. Three or four exchanges in, they were laughing together like old friends. To anyone walking by, it looked like four people who'd planned to meet at the cafe. And maybe some part of them was guided there for exactly that.

But here's what I can't stop thinking about: it was awkward first. It's ALWAYS awkward first. And then it wasn't.

That's the part that took me years to learn…connection is binary. It's a 1 or a 0, it’s either there or it's not.

Not everyone is open for the depth, and they don't have to be. But more people are than you'd think. When it's there, it's clear. They could have closed the conversation and gotten on with their day, and they didn't.

And when it's not there? It's not a YOU thing. A wise friend once told me there is no such thing as “rejection,” just a “lack of connection.” So when it’s not there, don’t take it personally, simply mosey on toward the next connection waiting for you.

So you don't need the perfect line. The same friend taught me the SAY ANYTHING Rule. You just need to say *anything*. Anything is enough to gauge whether the door is open.

The awkward isn't the stop sign. It's the toll booth.

Pay it. Say hi. Ask to share the table. Compliment the shoes. Ask about the book. Ask what is good at the cafe while you wait in line. Say anything — and let them show you what's on the other side.

Somebody out there is one small brave moment away from being your next favorite person.

Break through,
Joshua "Pay The Toll" Church


Hi friends,

"What the hell are you doing?! You don't even know how to play basketball!"

That's what a guy yelled at his teammate last night after our pickup game. A game they WON, by the way. And the guy he was yelling at was honestly one of the best shooters out there, and someone I always love playing with.  It sounded a lot like the worst insult from The Sandlot — "You play ball like a girl." Except this was a grown man in his forties to another grown ass man.

I've been playing with this guy for years now. And I've never once seen him smile on the court. Not after a good play. Not after a win. Not ever. He rolls his eyes at his teammates, mutters under his breath and has a running side commentary of everything everyone else is doing wrong.

And I found myself watching him thinking…are you even having fun out here?

Because we're not pros. Nobody's getting drafted (unfortunately). There's no trophy. We're a bunch of grown men showing up on a Monday night to run around a gym because it's supposed to be FUN.

That's the whole point.

And it got me wondering...if he shows up to a pickup game like that, how is he showing up to the rest of his life?

Because I think a lot of us are playing the game of life the exact same way. Eye rolling through our days. Muttering under our breath. Keeping a running tally of what everyone else is doing wrong, blaming and complaining. Grinding our teeth through the thing we literally chose.

We tell ourselves we'll have fun LATER. When the promotion hits. When the relationship shows up. When we finally arrive at wherever we think we're going.

But I've found that joy isn't waiting for you at the finish line. Joy is a muscle. And you don't build it later,  you build it in the pickup game, in the commute, in the grocery store, in the Monday night of your one wild life.

If you can't find fun in the game you chose to play, the problem ISN'T the game.

So today.. wherever you are, whatever you're doing, SMILE a little. Talk some trash. Celebrate your teammate. Laugh when you airball it. Remember you SIGNED UP for this.

We're supposed to be having fun out here!!!

Laughing all the way,

Joshua "Signed Up For This" Church

